03999nam a22005175i 9780520389045DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021060219  a97805203890457 a10.1515/97805203890452doi  a(DE-B1597)627806  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBP131b.S56 2022 4aBP131 7aREL0370102bisacsh04a297.1/2209223/eng/202201291 aShoemaker, Stephen J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCreating the Qur'an :bA Historical-Critical Study /cStephen J. Shoemaker. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (370 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Traditional Narrative of the Qur'an's Origins: A Scholarly Sunnism -- t2. ʿAbd al-Malik, al-Ḥajjāj, and the Composition of the Qur'an -- t3. Radiocarbon Dating and the Origins of the Qur'an -- t4. The Hijaz in Late Antiquity: Social and Economic Conditions in the Cradle of the Qur'an -- t5. Literacy, Orality, and the Qur'an's Linguistic Environment -- t6. Remembering Muhammad: Perspectives from Memory Science -- t7. Re-Remembering Muhammad: Oral Tradition and Collective Memory -- t8. The Qur'anic Codex as Process: Writing Sacred Tradition in Late Antiquity -- t9. The Qur'an's Historical Context According to the Qur'an -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aCreating the Qur'an presents the first systematic historical-critical study of the Qur'an's origins, drawing on methods and perspectives commonly used to study other scriptural traditions. Demonstrating in detail that the Islamic tradition relates not a single attested account of the holy text's formation, Stephen J. Shoemaker shows how the Qur'an preserves a surprisingly diverse array of memories regarding the text's early history and its canonization. To this he adds perspectives from radiocarbon dating of manuscripts, the linguistic history of Arabic, the social and cultural history of late ancient Arabia, and the limitations of human memory and oral transmission, as well as various peculiarities of the Qur'anic text itself. Considering all the relevant data to present the most comprehensive and convincing examination of the origin and evolution of the Qur'an available, Shoemaker concludes that the canonical text of the Qur'an was most likely produced only around the turn of the eighth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520389045?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520389045zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520389045/original  a978-3-11-076649-3 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA